### Overview

I'd like to update `extend`, so that the child has a refernce to its parent's constructor (`__parent__ = parent`). The main motivation is that I'd like to check to see if model B is a subclass of model A without instanciating it and using `instanceof`. 

As a disclaimer, `__parent__` would be used in a small ancestor-esque util, not product code.

### Relevant issues / tests
I checked #787, #1348, #342 and I don't think this solution addressed. I looked for relevant tests and could not find any. 


### Sample Code
Here's some throw-away code that could be written if `__parent__` were availble.

``` js
Model.childOf = function(objB) {
    var objA = this;
    while ((objA = objA.__parent__) !== undefined) {
        if (objA === objB) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    return false;
}

Model.ancestors = function() {
    var ancestors = [],
        ancestor = this;
    while ((ancestor = ancestor.__parent__) !== undefined) {
        ancestors.push(ancestor)
    }

    return ancestors;
}

var A = Backbone.Model.extend({}),
    B = A.extend({}),
    C = B.extend({}),
    D = C.extend({});

console.log('D, A', D.childOf(B));          // => true
console.log('A, B', A.childOf(B));          // => false
console.log('A, A', A.childOf(A));          // => false
console.log('Bs ancestors', B.ancestors()); // => [A, Backbone.Model]
```

The following code does not run the event handler:

```
events: {
  'scroll .selector' : 'scrollHandler'
}
```

The problem is that scroll events do not bubble. Backbone tries to bind the scroll event using the delegated syntax, like this:

```
this.$el.on('scroll', '.selector', this['scrollHandler'], this)
```

However, this fails since the event never bubbles to this.$el. Would it be appropriate to patch backbone events to treat scroll bindings differently, like:

```
if (!selector) {
  this.$el.on(event, handler)
} else if (isScrollEvent) {
  this.$(selector).on(event, handler)
} else {
  this.$el.on(event, selector, handler)
}
```

The limitation of this is elements would need to be children of this.$el already, but at least it would work in some cases.

Thoughts?

We listen to `sync`/`request` events and hook into the promise nature of the `xhr` to show loading status, disable buttons etc. For example, when adding a new comment, we use `{ wait: true}` and freeze the textarea and button. 

```javascript
// This could be in a view that is different than the code that does the request.
this.listentTo(model, 'request', function(model, xhr) {
  this.freezeAddComment();
  xhr.always(this.thawAddComment)
  .done(this.resetComment)
  .fail(this.showCommentError);
});
```

When using `Collection#create()` with `{ wait: true }`, the request to save the new model is lost.

Therefore, I suggest we add something like a `create` event that occurs on the collection after the request is made. Currently, we have a custom `sync` that does this:

```javascript
sync: function(method, model, options) {

  var xhr = Model.prototype.sync.apply(this, arguments);

  var collection = model.collection;
  if (method === 'create' && collection) {
    collection.trigger('create', model, collection, xhr, options);
  }

  return xhr;
}
```

@caseywebdev The `Collection::get` method defined by 01d9f0f9b1e85cb21a2940902bc8ba4280c8bca9 has this odd behavior when the collection contains a model with the id `"undefined"`: `collection.get(obj)` will return that model whenever `obj.id` is `undefined`. An odd edge case, I know, but believe it or not I ran into this in a production application... among other things, it means that

    new Backbone.Collection([{id: 'undefined'}, {id: 'foo'}, {id: 'bar'}])

will create a collection with length `1`.

What was wrong with the [Backbone 1.0.0 definition](https://github.com/jashkenas/backbone/blob/1.0.0/backbone.js#L786) of `get`, which explicitly checked for this case?

    return this._byId[obj.id != null ? obj.id : obj.cid || obj];

